  <static seed="288" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddingFractionsOfInches10.pg">
    <statement><p>A <m>2\times4</m> piece of lumber in your garage is <m>{64{\textstyle\frac{5}{32}}}</m> inches long. A second <m>2\times4</m> is <m>{45{\textstyle\frac{3}{32}}}</m> inches long. If you lay them end to end, what will the total length be?</p>
<p>The total length will be <fillin characters="7" name="AnSwEr0001"/> inches.</p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>109{\textstyle\frac{1}{4}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To find the total length in inches, we add the two lengths together.</p>
<p><m>\begin{aligned}
    {64{\textstyle\frac{5}{32}}}+{45{\textstyle\frac{3}{32}}} \amp  = 64+\frac{5}{32}+45+\frac{3}{32}\\
                \amp  = 109+\frac{5}{32}+\frac{3}{32}\\
                \amp  = 109+{{\frac{1}{4}}}\\
                \amp  = {109{\textstyle\frac{1}{4}}}
\end{aligned}</m></p>
<p>So the total length is <m>{109{\textstyle\frac{1}{4}}}</m> inches.</p>
</solution>
